column2: The Jarvis release over the weekend (September 26 and 27) was less than the Operating Diagram release because of a scheduling error.  The amount of under release was 1440 cfsh.  A compensating over release is being undertaken on September 28 and 29.
Jarvis released additional water to compensate for the under release caused by the lightning strike on September 23.
The Hinckley discharge was less than the Operating Diagram discharge because the powerhouse tripped offline due to a lightning strike.  The amount of under discharge was 988 cfsh.
The Jarvis discharge is scheduled to be 100 cfs above the Operating Diagram release for 24 hours starting 2pm Sept 15.  This will compensate for the under discharge that occurred on Sept 13 and 14.

The Hinckley discharge was less than the Operating Diagram discharge for 19 hours (5pm Sept 13 until noon Sept 14) due to a transmission constraint and a limitation on the bypass valve.  The amount of under discharge was 2331 cfsh.
Hinckley discharge was reduced to 250 cfs for the first 5 hours of the day in order to aid in the recovery of a drowning victim near the confluence with the Mohawk River.
The buoy float line at Hinckley dam was installed and the Hinckley discharge has returned to the Operating Diagram discharge (720 cfs) as of 1 pm today.
The Jarvis turbine release was increased to 1800 cfs at 4pm to drawdown the reservoir so that temporary installation of the buoy float line can take place before the Memorial Day weekend.

The Hinckley reservoir outflow (spillway + turbine) was increased to 1400 cfs in order to drawdown the reservoir to 1223.5 feet so that the buoy float line can be installed near the dam crest before the Memorial Day weekend.
The Jarvis turbine release was reduced down to the Operating Diagram release (1100 cfs) at 11:00am today because of the decreasing flood risk.
The Jarvis turbine release was increased to its capability (1800 cfs) at 3pm today to help reduce the flood potential.
The Jarvis turbine release was reduced down to the Operating Diagram release (1100 cfs) at 9:00am today because of the decreasing flood risk.
The Jarvis turbine release was increased to its capability (1850 cfs) at 10:00am today to help reduce the flood potential.
Reservoir elevation is estimated Jan 21-23 due to ice.
